# PART 1 Regression of childs height on mid-height of parent and gender 
library(ggplot2)
library(moderndive)
galton <- read.csv("galton_height.csv", header=T) 
galton$mid_parent_height <- (galton$Father + 1.08 * galton$Mother)/2

# Plot with same slope
ggplot(galton, aes(x = mid_parent_height, y = Height, color = Gender)) +
  geom_point() +
   geom_parallel_slopes(se=FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Child Height vs. Mid-Parent Height",
       x = "Mid-Parent Height",
       y = "Child Height") 

# Plot with different slope
ggplot(galton, aes(x = mid_parent_height, y = Height, color = Gender)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Child Height vs. Mid-Parent Height",
       x = "Mid-Parent Height",
       y = "Child Height")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# Q1 Answer: Both plots return similar parallel slopes even when it is not forced to be parallel.

# Regression with parallel slopes
fit <- lm(Height ~ mid_parent_height + Gender, data = galton)
summary(fit)

Q2 Answer: Yes, both mid_parent_height and GenderM are highly significant predictors of child height. I can come to this conclusion because both variables have very small p-values (<2e-16) on their t-test.

Q3 Answer: The coefficient for mid_parent_height is 0.70282. This means that for a 1 inch increase in mid-parent height, the expected increase in childs height is 0.70282 inches.

No, the effect of mid-parent height does not depend on the gender of the child. The effect of gender is captured by the GenderM coefficient, which estimates the average difference in height between males and females. But this gender difference does not interact with the effect of mid-parent height in this model.

Q4 Answer: No, the interaction term mid_parent_height:GenderM is not significant (p-value = 0.814, much higher than 0.05).

Q5 Answer: For daughter (GenderM = 0): 0.69337 inches. For son (GenderM = 1): 0.69337 + 0.01870 = 0.71207 inches. The difference between son and daughter is not statistically significant, since the interaction term is not significant.

Q6 Answer: The slope estimate for the model fitted on just daughters is 0.69337.

This matches the slope from the interaction model for daughters (when GenderM = 0).

Fitting separate models for daughters and sons gives very similar results to the interaction model.

Q7 Answer: I would choose the Q2 model. The interaction term in the Q4 model is not statistically significant, so the non-significant interaction term and lack of evidence for different slopes by gender means the simpler model in Q2 is preferred. It does not include an unnecessary interaction term that overfits the data.

#Recall Q2 model
fit <- lm(Height ~ mid_parent_height + Gender, data = galton)

# scatterplot
ggplot(fit, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid))+
  geom_point() +
  xlab("Fitted Values") +
  ylab("Residuals")

# histogram
ggplot(fit, aes(x = fit$residuals)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20) +
  xlab("Residuals")

# qq plot
ggplot(galton, aes(sample = residuals(fit)/sd(residuals(fit)))) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line() +
  xlab("Theoretical Quantiles") +
  ylab("Standardized Residuals") +
  ggtitle("QQ Plot of Standardized Residuals")

# Q8 Answer: # Residual vs.Fitted: No obvious patterns, residuals scatter randomly around 0 across fitted values. # Histogram: Approximately normal distribution with a slight right skew # QQ Plot: Residuals follow theoretical quantiles closely in the middle. There are some departures in tails, with heavier tails empirically than expected under normality.

Overall, the assumptions of normality and homoscedasticity appear to be met, while there are some departues in the QQ plot tails. The multiple r-squared value is 0.6371. This model explains about 63.71% of the variation in child heights based on the mid-parent heights and child genders.

#PART 2-Regression of childs height on father and mothers height 
galton$Gender <- as.factor(galton$Gender)
galton$Height_adjusted <- ifelse(galton$Gender == "M", galton$Height, galton$Height - 5)

model_no_interaction <- lm(Height_adjusted ~ Father + Mother, data = galton)
summary(model_no_interaction)

Q17 Answer:

#The coefficients for MidParentHeight and Gender are: # MidParentHeight: 0.70282 # GenderM: 5.22817

Q16 vs.Q17 Comparison:

The reason for the difference in coefficients for Father and Mother vs.MidParentHeight is that the MidParentHeight formula applies a weight of 1.08 to the mothers height before taking the average with the fathers height.

This accounts for the mothers height having a slightly different impact on the childs height compared to the fathers height. By using the MidParentHeight formula, this weight is implicitly incorporated into the model, whereas in the model without interaction (Q16), the weights for Father and Mother are estimated separately.

However, the coefficient for GenderM is the same in both models, as it represents the average height difference between males and females, despite the inclusion of MidParentHeight or separate Father and Mother variables.
